Let the point of tangency on $y^2 = 4x$ be $(a,b).$  Then $b^2 = 4a.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return(sqrt(4*x));
}

real func2 (real x) {
  return(-x^2/32);
}

draw(graph(func,-0.5,5),red);
draw(graph(-func,-0.5,5),red);
draw(graph(func2,-8,8),blue);
draw((-10,0)--(10,0));
draw((0,-10)--(0,10));

dot("$y^2 = 4x$", (5,func(5)), E, red);
dot("$x^2 = -32y$", (8,func2(8)), N, blue);
dot("$(a,b)$", (1,2), NW);
[/asy]

The slope of the tangent line to $y^2 = 4x$ at $(a,b)$ is
\[\frac{d}{dx} \sqrt{4x} = \frac{2}{\sqrt{4x}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{a}}.\]Hence, the equation of the tangent line is
\[y - b = \frac{1}{\sqrt{a}} (x - a).\]We can write this as
\[y = \frac{1}{\sqrt{a}} x + b - \frac{\sqrt{a}}{1}.\]

Let the point of tangency on $x^2 = -32y$ be $(c,d).$  Then $c^2 = -32d.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return(sqrt(4*x));
}

real func2 (real x) {
  return(-x^2/32);
}

draw(graph(func,-0.5,5),red);
draw(graph(-func,-0.5,5),red);
draw(graph(func2,-8,8),blue);
draw((-10,0)--(10,0));
draw((0,-10)--(0,10));

dot("$y^2 = 4x$", (5,func(5)), E, red);
dot("$x^2 = -32y$", (8,func2(8)), N, blue);
dot("$(a,b)$", (1,2), NW);
dot("$(c,d)$", (8,-2), SE);
[/asy]

The slope of the tangent line to $x^2 = -32y$ at $(c,d)$ is
\[\frac{d}{dx} \left( -\frac{x^2}{32} \right) = -\frac{x}{16} = -\frac{c}{16}.\]Hence, the equation of the tangent line is
\[y - d = -\frac{c}{16} (x - c).\]We can write this as
\[y = -\frac{c}{16} x + d + \frac{c^2}{16}.\]

Since these two tangent lines are the same line,
\[\frac{1}{\sqrt{a}} = -\frac{c}{16}\]and
\[b - \frac{\sqrt{a}}{1} = d + \frac{c^2}{16}.\]Then $c = -\frac{16}{\sqrt{a}},$ so
\[d + \frac{c^2}{16} = d + \frac{256}{a} = b - \frac{\sqrt{a}}{1}.\]Also, $b^2 = 4a$ and $c^2 = -32d,$ so
\[d + \frac{256}{a} = \sqrt{4a} - \frac{\sqrt{a}}{1} = \frac{3 \sqrt{a}}{1}\]and
\[d = -\frac{c^2}{32} = -\frac{256}{a}.\]Then
\[-\frac{256}{a} + \frac{256}{a} = \frac{3 \sqrt{a}}{1},\]so $\sqrt{a} = 0.$  This is impossible, so there is no such tangent line.  Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{\text{no solution}}.$

